Regarding the issue with the full-size image exceeding the modal's bounds, you can address this by adding appropriate CSS to ensure that the image will be scaled down to fit within the modal's dimensions. You can achieve this by setting a `max-width` and `max-height` on the image and using `object-fit` to maintain its aspect ratio.

Here's how you might update your `Modal` component's CSS:

```css
.modal-content {
  background-color: #fefefe;
  margin: 15% auto;
  padding: 20px;
  border: 1px solid #888;
  width: 80%;
  max-width: 600px; /* You can adjust this to your preference */
  overflow: hidden; /* Add this to handle scrollbars if the image is still too large */
}

.modal-content img {
  width: 100%;
  max-height: 80vh; /* This will ensure the image is not taller than 80% of the viewport height */
  object-fit: contain; /* This makes sure that the image is scaled properly */
}
```

This CSS will:
- Set the maximum width of the modal.
- Prevent the image from being taller than 80% of the viewport height.
- Ensure that the image is scaled to fit within the modal while maintaining its aspect ratio.

With `object-fit: contain`, the image will scale down to fit within the given dimensions while preserving its aspect ratio, without being stretched or squashed.

Additionally, the `overflow: hidden;` property on the `.modal-content` is helpful if the image is still too large for any reason—it hides the scrollbars and makes sure the content does not overflow the modal box.

By adjusting the `max-width`, `max-height`, and the modal `margin`, you can ensure the image fits well within the user's screen while inside the modal.

